\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Discussion\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 This study demonstrates a significant association between reduced gut microbiome diversity and increased depressive symptom severity in adults. Individuals with moderate to severe depressive symptoms exhibited lower microbial diversity and altered taxonomic composition, characterized by reduced abundance of beneficial short-chain fatty acid\'96producing bacteria.\
Short-chain fatty acids, particularly butyrate, play a crucial role in maintaining intestinal barrier integrity, regulating immune responses, and modulating neuroinflammation. Reduced production of these metabolites may contribute to systemic inflammation and altered neurotransmitter signaling, mechanisms implicated in depression pathophysiology.\
The observed increase in potentially pro-inflammatory bacterial taxa further supports the hypothesis that dysbiosis may promote low-grade inflammation, which has been consistently linked to depressive symptoms. These findings align with previous animal and human studies suggesting bidirectional communication between the gut microbiome and the central nervous system.\
Strengths of this study include comprehensive clinical phenotyping, adjustment for multiple confounders, and detailed microbiome analysis. Limitations include the cross-sectional design, which precludes causal inference, and reliance on self-reported depressive symptoms rather than diagnostic interviews.\
Future longitudinal and interventional studies are needed to determine whether modifying the gut microbiome through dietary interventions, probiotics, or fecal microbiota transplantation can improve depressive symptoms.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Conclusion\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Reduced gut microbiome diversity is significantly associated with increased depressive symptom severity in adults. These findings support the involvement of the gut\'96brain axis in depression and suggest that microbiome-targeted interventions may represent a promising adjunctive approach in depression management.\
